The Telegraph - Calcutta

 Anand, Leko settle for draw

Linares: Viswanathan Anand played a safe game and settled for a quick draw against Hungarian Peter Leko in a second round tie of the Linares Super Grandmasters chess tournament here. 

Garri Kasparov of Russia reached the top of the table after three rounds with a crushing victory over local lad Frabcisco Vallejo Pons. 

While Kasparov, who is on two points from three games, is half a point ahead of Anand in this category-20 event, the Indian ace has got 1.5 from two boards which suits him perfectly with 11 rounds still to come. 

The event is being played on a double round-robin basis between seven players and the total prize pool is euro 297,000. 

Playing the Petroff defence as black, Anand started venturing in to tactics on the 18th move with an exchange sacrifice and Leko had no answers to some very forceful manoeuvres. Sacrificing another piece, Anand forced a draw by repetition of moves. The game lasted just 24 moves. 

Kasparov pla-yed to achieve equality easily but was pleased to find Vallejo trying in the queen?s gambit accepted game. 

The Spaniard, white, started off well before deviating to a difficult situation that led to wild complications. Kasparov took his chances in the middle game and eventually won a couple of pawns to force resignation in 29 moves. 

It was a relatively easy draw between fide world cha-mpion Rustam Kasimdzhanov and Michael Adams. 

